ev10.title: SAZAN
ev10.description: On 25 April, Franceschino sets sail again and after 4 days of navigation and 370 miles he arrives on 30 April, on the eve of Ascension Day (which in 1383 fell on 1 May), «ad montem Saxinum, qui est in capite Sgavonie [scil. Sclavonie], ubi distant milliaria CCCLXX». This may possibly be Sazan, an islet in Albania opposite Valona in the Otranto Channel, known to Greeks and Romans as Sason.

ev15.title: RAMLA (AL-RAMLA)
ev15.description: From Jaffa, Franceschino reaches Ramla, in the Judean valley, on 21 May, which he defines as «prima terra Saracinorum»: «Die XXI Maii discessi de Zaffa et ivi Ramam, qui est prima terra Saracinorum, ubi distant milliaria XII». In Ramla, the cimator also paid a tax and probably visited the Basilica of St George, today in Lidda, 5 km from Ramla, where the saint was martyred: «Item Rame: grossi V ½. Item Rame, ubi truncatum fuit caput Sancti Georgii: solidi I».

ev3.title: THROUGH UMBRIA: RIETI, SPOLETO, FOLIGNO, NOCERA UMBRA, CANTIANO
ev3.description: Leaving Rome on 18 March, Franceschino begins his journey back to Venice, first stopping in Rieti and then crossing Umbria, staying in Spoleto, Foligno and Nocera Umbra, up to Cantiano, nowadays in the province of Pesaro-Urbino on the border with Umbria: «“A” Rethi hospitatus fui, ubi distant milliaria XXII. “A” Spoliti hospitatus fui, ubi distant milliaria XXVIII. In prandio fui Folligni et hospitatus fui “a” Nocea, ubi distant milliaria XXIIIIa. “A” Cantiana hospitatus fui, ubi distant milliaria XXVII». It is likely that Franceschino took his main meal of the day in Foligno before leaving for Nocera Umbra, where he stayed overnight. The latin word prandium indicates the first or the main meal of the day.

ev19.title: BETHANY (AL-EIZARIYA)
ev19.description: From the list of Franceschino’s expenses in the Holy Land we learn that he also travelled to Bethany, a biblical village in Judea (today known by its Arabic name Al-Eizariya) on the south-eastern side of the Mount of Olives: the place that is remembered in the Gospels as the village where Lazarus lived. Here he visited the Tomb of Lazarus, the supposed site of the famous miracle of Lazarus’ resurrection: «Ad monumentum Sancti Lazari: solidi I».

ev11.title: MODON (Μεθώνη)
ev11.description: After 300 miles of navigation, Franceschino landes at Modone on 2 May, where he stays for 3 days for supplies: «Et ibi intravi in terram Grecorum […], et applicui “a” Modom die secunda Maii, et ibi steti diebus tribus causa fulciendi illis rebus quibus indigebamus, et ibi distant milliaria CCC». At the time Modone was one of the most important naval bases of the Venetian Republic in the Ionian Sea: all ships sailing from Venice to the East and all pilgrims' ships bound for the Holy Land stopped over there. Modone and nearby Corone, on the southern tip of the Morea, were known as oculi capitales Communis, i.e. ‘the two eyes of the Republic’.

ev14.title:
THE ARRIVAL IN THE HOLY LAND:
JAFFA (YĀFĀ)
ev14.description: On 14 May, Franceschino sets sail from Rhodes and sails six days to Jaffa in Palestine, known as “the oldest port in the world”. It is remarkable that our cimator sailed from Rhodes to Jaffa without stopping in Cyprus, as was the norm for journeys to the Holy Land: «Die XIIIIa inter nonam et vesperas discessi “da” Rodom et applicui “a” Zafa in diebus VI inter nonam et vesperas, ubi distant milliaria VI centum». From the list of the sums of money that Franceschino paid to the Saracens, which in the manuscript follows the itinerarium («Iste sunt expense solvende Saracenis, non pro comedendo neque pro bibendo»), we know that the cimator paid a tax to enter the port of Jaffa: «Primo “a” Zaffa: florini unum, grossi IIII». The 'grosso' was a silver florin. As recalled by Niccolò da Poggibonsi, a Franciscan traveller and author of the Libro d'Oltramare, written after his pilgrimage to the Holy Land in 1345-1350: «all’entrata e all’uscita si paga al detto porto [di Giaffa] V drame per testa e due drame allo ‘nterpreto. El detto ammiraglio scrive tutti i peregrini, e come sono fatti e di che grandezza e di che pelo e tutti i segni che puote avere per la persona, e poi gli manda all’ammiraglio di Rama» (POGGIBONSI, Libro d’Oltramare 1881, vol. I, pp. 26-28). Similarly, as soon as Franceschino arrived in Jaffa, he spent 13 soldi on a "turcimanno": «“a” Zaffa, pro “lo” torcimano: solidi XIII». At the that time, 'turcimanno' meant a generic interpreter-translator, an expert of Oriental languages. But the largest expense that Franceschino had to face was obviously for the galley on which he embarked from Venice and returned: «pro nollo galee causa eundi et revertendi Venetias: florini VII ½».

ev17.title:
JORDAN RIVER: THE SITE OF JESUS' BAPTISM
(AL-MAGHTAS)
ev17.description: Franceschino then moves on to the Jordan River, which is 28 miles (about 45 km) from Jerusalem: «Ad flumen Iordanis distant milliaria XXVIII». The list of expenses also gives evidence of the amount Franceschino paid to get near the river, probably to visit the place of Jesus’ baptism: «Ad eundum ad flumen Iordanis: grossi I, solidi II».

ev2.title: ROME
ev2.description: It is likely that the cimator, in order to reach Rome, followed the route of the Via Francigena, which, as it is well-known, passes through Pontremoli. Franceschino claims that it took him 16 days to reach Rome: he arrived on 5 March and left 13 days later, on 18 March: «Die XVIIIa Martii discessi Roma et hospitatus fui “a la” villa, ubi distant milliaria XVIIIa». The villa where Franceschino stayed must have been on the Via Salaria, the way which he probably followed on his way from Rome to Rieti. It is likely that Franceschino stopped in Rome to visit the city: Rome, the second holy city for the Christian world, certainly was an important destination for pilgrims. The pilgrimage to Rome, which was less challenging than the pilgrimage to the Holy Land, was no less important from a spiritual point of view, as a place of worship of the early martyrs and a papal centre involved in dispensing indulgences.

ev5.title: GORO AND THE ABBEY OF POMPOSA
ev5.description: Franceschino raises anchor from Rimini and in two days reaches the port of Goro which is in the province of Ferrara and now is located in the southernmost part of the Po delta. It is probable that the cimator chose to reach Goro by sea to avoid the marshy lands of the Po valley: «Et ibi ascendi in mari, et die secunda applicui ad portum “de Goro” qui est abbatis Pompoxe, ubi distant miliaria LXXXX». According to Franceschino’s account, at that time the territory of Goro belonged to the Abbot of Pomposa, whose abbey, once surrounded by the waters of the Po (insula pomposiana), is nowadays in the municipality of Codigoro, adjacent to Goro. It is important to note that the author employs the vernacular form portum de Goro instead of the more correct portum Gori: although written in Latin, Franceschino’s itinerarium is characterised by the presence of strong vernacularisms (e.g. the use of the preposition a with the meaning of motion to place, sometimes used in conjunction with the article la: «hospitatus fui “a la” villa»), typical of the usus of the author, whose knowledge of Latin was evidently very elementary.

ev7.title: VENICE
ev7.description: The cimator arrives at Malamocco, a district of Venice. The distance of 55 miles reported by Franceschino refers to the Chioggia-Malamocco distance, while 5 miles is the short distance separating Malamocco from Venice. Franceschino left Venice on 6 April for the Holy Land. It is probable that it was in Venice that Franceschino took care of the chartering of the galley and the necessities for the journey: «Item Giocza, et Venetias “a” Mallamocho, ubi distant milliaria LV. Die Sabbati summo mane applicui Venetias hora misse, ubi distant milliaria V. Discessi Venetiis die VIa Aprilis».
ev7.eventMediaCaption: Venetian galley transporting pilgrims to the Holy Land, taken from the travel diary of Conrad Grünenberg (1487)

ev8.title:
ISLAND OF ST. ANDREW
(SVETI ANDRIJA)
ev8.description: Once he had left Venice, after 100 miles (about 160 km) Franceschino lands «in una insula in qua erat una ecclesia Sancti Andree, in qua morantur duo heremite», where he stops for two days. It is possible that this is the Island of St. Andrew, south of Rovinj, Croatia, along the western coast of Istria, where the Benedictines had founded the monastery of St. Andrew in the 6th century. At the time when Franceschino arrives, the island must have been almost uninhabited. This condition would explain the presence of two hermits: the island was actually abandoned during the 13th century and was given new life only in the 15th century with the arrival of the Observant Franciscans. On 11 April, Franceschino sets out again and stops for three days in an unknown place, about 15 miles (about 25 km) away, before reaching another destination, whose name he again omits, 35 miles (about 56 km) away, where he stops for a day. Considering the distances, these must still be Istrian places. These two close stops are perhaps due to some unforeseen event, perhaps unfavourable winds or rough seas, since Franceschino specifies that he stays in these places propter fortunam: «Die <…> aplicui in una insula in qua erat una ecclesia Sancti Andree, in qua morantur duo heremite, et ibi steti diebus duobus, ubi distant milliaria centum. Die XIa itineravi, et ibi steti per tres dies propter fortunam, ubi distant milliaria XV, et in sero discessi et itineravi illa nocte cum die sequenti, et steti ibi per fortunam una die, milliaria XXXV».
ev8.eventMediaCaption: Benedictine monastery on the island of St. Andrew

ev18.title: THE VALLEY OF JOSAPHAT AND THE CHURCH OF THE ASSUMPTION OF MARY
ev18.description: Franceschino continues to visit the places of worship and moves on to the Valley of Josaphat, east of Jerusalem between the Temple Mount and the Mount of Olives: «De terra vallis Iosaphat distant milliaria III». As we learn from the list of expenses, Franceschino visited the Church of the Assumption of Mary, better known as the Tomb of the Virgin Mary, located at the foot of the Mount of Olives in the Valley of Josaphat: «Ad monumentum nostre Domine: solidi II. In montem Oliveti: solidi II».
ev18.eventMediaCaption: Church of the Assumption of Mary

ev12.title: HERAKLION (Ηράκλειο)
ev12.description: After leaving Modon on 6 May, Franceschino sailes for 32 hours to Candia, one of the most important cities on the island of Crete, which came under Venetian rule in 1204, after the 4th Crusade. Here he stops for a day and a half before setting off again: «Summo mane discessi “da” Modon in die Sancti Iohannis ante portam latinam, cuius festum est die VI<sup>a</sup> Maii, et ivi in Candiam in XXXII horis, et ibi steti die una cum dimidia, ubi distant milliaria CCC».

ev13.title: RHODES (Ρόδος)
ev13.description: On 10 May our cimator sets sail again and continues sailing for three days and another 300 miles, arriving in Rhodes, where he stops for a day and a half: «De Candia discessi in mane in festo Pasce Rosarum, cuius festum fuit die X<sup>a</sup> Maii, et ivi Rodom in tribus diebus et ibi steti die una cum dimidia, ubi distant milliaria CCC». The Easter of Roses is a Christian festivity celebrated during the Pentecost mass, with a shower of red rose petals falling on the faithful to commemorate the descent of the Holy Spirit on Mary and the Apostles.

ev16.title: THE ARRIVAL IN JERUSALEM
ev16.description: On 23 May, Franceschino reaches his destination: almost three months after his departure from Pontremoli, the humble cimator arrives in Jerusalem. He visited a few places in the surroundings, just the few that a modest pilgrim could afford, riding a donkey that was paid by him «florini I ½»: «Die XXIII Maii aplicui Yerusalem, ubi distant milliaria XXVIII. Ad flumen Iordanis distant milliaria XXVIII. De terra vallis Iosaphat distant milliaria III. In Bethleem, ubi Christus natus est, distant milliaria III». As can be seen from the list of his expenses, Franceschino visited the Basilica of the Holy Sepulchre and also the Shrine of the Holy Sepulchre, for which there were two different "entrance tickets": «Ad intrandum in ecclesia Sepulcri: florini V, grossi I […]. Pro intrando in Sepulcro: solidi XVI».
ev16.eventMediaCaption: Jerusalem, Basilica of the Holy Sepulchre

ev1.title: DEPARTURE FROM PONTREMOLI
ev1.description: The manuscript 1153 of Yale’s Beinecke Library contains at folios 144v-145r a brief report of the journey to the Holy Land, made in 1383 by Franceschinus cimator de Pontremulo, a humble cloth remover from Pontremoli. The only work by Franceschino that is still extant today is this brief itinerarium. It retraces the stages of the piligrim’s journey to the Holy Land, starting from Pontremoli on 18 February 1383. The route undertaken by Franceschino turns out to be, at least in its initial part, an anomalous one: although the cimator was close to Genoa, he decides to set sail from Venice to reach the Holy Land, passing through Rome, the second stage of his journey. Franceschino tells us that Rome is 300 terrestrial miles away from Pontremoli, about 480 km. Indeed this is a rather precise indication, since the real distance between Pontremoli and Rome is about 450 km: «Ego Franceschinus cimator de Pontremulo discessi causa eundi in Yerusalem ad visitandum illa sancta loca, et sic ivi Romam in dietis XVI, ubi distant milliaria CCC per terram».

text.headline: DEPARTURE FROM PONTREMOLI
text.text:
The manuscript 1153 of Yale’s Beinecke Library contains at folios 144v-145r a brief report of the journey to the Holy Land, made in 1383 by Franceschinus cimator de Pontremulo, a humble cloth remover from Pontremoli. The only work by Franceschino that is still extant today is this brief itinerarium. It retraces the stages of the piligrim’s journey to the Holy Land, starting from Pontremoli on 18 February 1383. The route undertaken by Franceschino turns out to be, at least in its initial part, an anomalous one: although the cimator was close to Genoa, he decides to set sail from Venice to reach the Holy Land, passing through Rome, the second stage of his journey. Franceschino tells us that Rome is 300 terrestrial miles away from Pontremoli, about 480 km. Indeed this is a rather precise indication, since the real distance between Pontremoli and Rome is about 450 km: «Ego Franceschinus cimator de Pontremulo discessi causa eundi in Yerusalem ad visitandum illa sancta loca, et sic ivi Romam in dietis XVI, ubi distant milliaria CCC per terram».

text.headline: CHIOGGIA
text.text:
From Goro Franceschino reaches Chioggia: «Et ibi ascendi in mari, et die secunda applicui ad portum “de Goro” qui est abbatis Pompoxe […]. Item Giocza». The spelling Giocza is perhaps influenced by the local pronunciation of the town, Ćioxa.

ev9.title: ZADAR
ev9.description: Franceschino arrives in Zadar on 17 April and after another five-day journey he arrives on 22 April «in una insula super Sclavonina [scil. Sclavonia]», an island in Croatia, 80 miles (about 128 km) away from Zadar, where he stayed for two days. In the 13th century the term Sclavonia was used by the Venetians to indicate the dominions of the Serenissima on the Dalmatian coast and in the Balkan hinterland: «Die XVII applicui “a” Zare, ubi distant milliaria centum, et in diebus V ivi in una insula super Sclavonina [scil. Sclavonia], et ibi sunt due ecclesie, et ibi steti duobus diebus per fortunam, ubi distant milliaria LXXX».

ev20.title: BETHLEHEM
ev20.description: After visiting Jerusalem, the Jordan River and the Valley of Josaphat, Franceschino recalls as his last stop Bethlehem, the place of Jesus’ nativity, 3 miles (about 6 km) from Jerusalem (the actual distance between Jerusalem and Bethlehem is about 8 km): «Die XXIII Maii aplicui Yerusalem, ubi distant milliaria XXVIII. Ad flumen Iordanis distant milliaria XXVIII. De terra vallis Iosaphat distant milliaria III. In Bethleem, ubi Christus natus est, distant milliaria III». Here Franceschino spent solidi IIII, perhaps to visit the Basilica of the Nativity: «In Bethlem: solidi IIII».
